    <text>
        <body>
            <div xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Damiaan van Vissenaken to Miklós Oláh (Ghent, 22 July
                    1532)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">Lactantius did not suspect false believers by accident;
                            he feels the same way. The gods should ruin Jakob Jespersen, along with
                            his follies. He has engaged his daughter to Lieven Algoet, and the day
                            of the wedding has been set for 6 August, for which they have invited
                            Oláh as well. He is sending him the New Testament.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Damianus Vissenacus Nicolao Olao secretario etc. reginae Mariae.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.2">Non imprudenter mihi <persName>Lactantius ille
                        Firmianus</persName><note type="critic" xml:id="note.1">Lucius Caecilius
                        Firmianus Lactantius (ca. 250–ca. 325) was an early Christian author and an
                        advisor of Emperor Constantine I.</note> fecisse videtur, Olae Clarissime,
                    qui nihil unquam tam suspectum habuit, quam false religiosos<note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.2">Lact. <hi rend="italic">Divinarum Institutionum Libri</hi>,
                        Liber 1: De falsa religione.</note> atque adeo ipsa fata, quae profecto nemo
                    unquam magis despuere magisque traducere debet, atque ego. Sed quorsum haec,
                    inquies? Certe alias tecum profusius, iam animi turbo cetera eructare non
                    patitur, nisi hoc unum, videlicet <persName>Iacobum Danum</persName><note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.3">Jakob Jespersen.</note> tuum (citra offensam
                    dixerim) me relegare in <placeName>Acharontis</placeName><note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.4">In Ancient Greek mythology, Acheron river was known as the
                        “river of woe”.</note> abyssum, quem diideaeque omnes perdant cum sua
                    confidentia atque scurrilitate, eundemque apud nos tesseram fregisse<note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.5">‘to break up the alliance’.</note> tibi
                    persuadeas. De <persName>Levino</persName><note type="critic" xml:id="note.6"
                        >Lieven Algoet.</note> nostro, quo tibi obsequium meum adversum te apertius
                    declararem, non potui non abstinere, suae voluptati obtemperans, quin sponsorem
                    agens ipsi adolenscenti, profecto vel tuo iudicio haud mediocribus honoribus
                    dignissimo, filiam meam desponderem. Itaque illum tibi iam sponsum remitto ad
                    nos brevi rediturum, si promissis stare noluerit, neque vulgo esse fabulam, nam
                    nuptiarum dies Augusti sextus constitutus est, quem tu decorare tua praesentia
                    ne <del corresp="Olahus">digneris</del><add corresp="Olahus" type="corr"
                        >dedigneris</add> etiam atque etiam obtestamur <del corresp="Olahus"
                        >ocissime</del>. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.3">Ex museo nostro XI. Kalendas Augusti <placeName>Gandavi</placeName>
                    1532.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.4">Novum Testamentum dono mittimus, quod tibi gratum fore mihi
                    persuadeo.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
